Overall effects of aldosterone
  • Increased sodium reabsorption by increaseding ENaC expression
  • Increased sodium reabsprotion -> increased luminal negativity -> K+ AND H+ are drawn out.
  • Also, Na/K+ basolateral ATPase is stimulated by aldosterone.
  • Also, direct stimulation of H+ secretory ATPase.

Therefore, effect is hypervolemia, increased Sodium reabsorption, hypokalemia and metabolic alkalosis.

Mechanism of the effects of aldosterone

It's a steroid so it binds to cytoplasmic receptors.

  • Principal cells of late distal tubule and collecting ducts
    • Increases expression of ENaC channels (apical) and and Na/K ATPase (basolateral).
  • Intercalated cells of the distal tubule and collecting ducts
    • Aldosterone acts on these cells only in the presence of angiotensin II
    • Alpha intercalated cells - Increases expression of H+ ATPase -> increased secretion of H+ into the lumen
    • Non Alpha intercalated cells - increased chloride reabsorption and increased bicarbonate excretion.

The most prominent findings are hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and a mild non–anion-gap metabolic acidosis due to the loss of the sodium-retaining and potassium and hydrogen ion-secreting action of aldosterone - Source

  • Hypercalcemia also occurs : cause is not known.

Causes of pulseless electrical activity

Pathogenesis : the cardiac muscle is unable to produced a conctraction which ejects enough blood to produce a pulse.
Conditions causing sudden changes in preload, afterload or contractility can cause PEA.

  • Preload reduction -> severe hypovolemia, obstructing pulmonary embolus, cardiac tamponade.
  • Decreased contractility -> commonest cause for PEA is hypoxia (insuffient ATP for contraction), hypocalcemia (calcium is required for sliding filament contraction),
  • Increased afterload is very unlikle to cause PEA
  • The H's and T's also are all causes of PEA.
    Source

"3 and 3 rule of Desbiens"

3 commonest causes of PEA:

  1. Sever hypovolemia
  2. Pump failure - massive MI or severe heart failure.
  3. obstruction of flow
    • 3 main causes of obstruction of circulation:
      1. Tension pneumothorax
      2. Cardiac tamponade
      3. Massive pulmonary embolus

Asthma and COPD are both diseases of chronic airway obstruction:
Common features are:

  1. chronic cough, sputpum production, dyspnoea, wheezing, recurrent LRTI
  2. Exposure to envinronmental hazards
  3. Chest X ray - may show hyperinflation, bullae
  4. Examination - may be normal or may have ronchi / crepitations.
Asthma COPD
Chronic airflow limitation - i.e not completely reversible by bronchodilation
In adults, it's difficult to distinguish from asthma
Defn: Chronic airway inflammation, symptoms vary over time and in intesity, with variable expiratory airflow limitation Defn: persistent and progressive airflow limitation in the background of chronic inflammatory changes of the airways

It is recognized that may patients have Asthma COPD Overlap Syndrome (ACOS).

A few points on basic physiology

Innervation of bronchial smooth muscle

Innervation of bronchial smooth muscle is predominantly parasympathetic, not sympathetic.
Cholinergic parasympathetic nerves mediate bronchospasm while noncholinergic parasympathetic nerves mediate bronchodilatation.

Circadian rhythms in asthma

#2022GM-MAY Q14

Asthma is a disease with a strong circadian rhythm; it is characteristic of asthma that symptoms worsen in the early hours of the morning around 4:00 am.
Both FEV1 and PEF vary in a circadian manner in healthy individuals with a nadir at approximately 4:00 am. However, in asthma, the amplitude of the circadian rhythm of both FEV1 and PEF is greatly magnified.

Inspiratory tests

Source

Definitions:
Forced inspiratory vital capacity:

The maximal volume of air which can be inspired during forced inspiration from a position of full expiration.

FIV1:

volume of air inspired in the first second during forced inspiration from full expiration.

Forced expiration increases intra airway pressure and widens extrathoracic airways. However, forced inspiration conversely causes the extrthoracic airways to narrow to the the negative intraluminal pressure.
Accordingly extrathoracic airway obstruction is best detected during a forced inspiration

Therefore,
$$
\LARGE {{\upuparrows}}\space \frac{Maximum\space \mathbf{Expiratory} \space Flow \space at \space 50% \space VC}{Maximum\space \mathbf{Inspiratory} \space Flow \space at \space 50% \space VC} ⇒ Extrathorac \space obstruction
$$

[!WARNING]
It seems like the common way of measuring this ratio is FIV / FEV, the opposite of what is given above, as seen here

Inspiratory tests are not affected by reductions in lung recoil. (so in emphysema, FEV1 will be reduced by FIV1 will be unchange)
